Dataset is taken from Kaggle and the link to dataset is https://www.kaggle.com/trolukovich/food5k-image-dataset. This dataset has 3 folders training, validation and testing and images in each of them for train, validation and test purposes which are used as it is after unzipping the dataset.¶

ImageDataGenerator is an easy way to load and augment images in batches for image classification tasks. It ensures that the machine doesn't see the same image twice to avoid overfitting.¶

Convolutional Neural Networks Model Building for Image Classification into Food and Non-Food¶

Model 1

3 Convolutional Layers with 16,32 and 64 number of filters, kernel/window size of 33, relu activation function, Maxpooling layer of 22 and dropout of 0.5

3 Maxpooling layers to reduce the size of the image after convolution

Flatten to make the 2D output to feature vector to be used by Fuly Connected NN layer with 256 neurons and 1 output

In [22]:
model = Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(16, (3, 3), input_shape=(256, 256,3)))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(256))
model.add(Activation('relu'))
model.add(Dense(1))
model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

Train the model using the 3000 images with 1500 images each of food items and 1500 of non food images takes a lot of time.¶

The graph for the Training vs Validation Accuracy over the 10 epochs show that the model is not overfitting. But there is slight deviation from the Training accuracy of Validation accuracy.

For the graph of Training Loss vs Validation loss, after the 1st epoch the train loss tends to decrease while the testing loss is more than train loss. It doesn't increase rapidly but the difference between the 2 is almost the same after the 4th epoch.

Dropout is used to avoid overfitting by dropping out randomly around 20% nodes after each update cycle. It is only used during training the data to reduce the complexity of the network thereby reducing the chances of overfitting

From the graph of Training vs Validation accuracy with different dropout shows that after 4th epoch the train and test accuracy tend to move in opposite direction with train accuracy increasing and at the same time validation accuracy decreases. This gap is getting more after 8th epoch.

From the graph of Training vs Validation loss shows the same for the loss. After 4th epoch train loss decreases whereas validation tends to move in a opposite direction and farther away after the 8th epoch. It may increase further causing the model to overfit as the gap is widening between the 2.

EarlyStopping is used stop the model from training after certain iterations/epochs to prevent overfitting. There can be situations where after certain number of epochs the validation accuracy doesn't improve even though the training accuracy increases leading to overfitting. In such cases, we would to stop training the model at that instance which is where EarlyStopping is used.

EarlyStopping to prevent the model from overfitting. Stops training the model if after 3 epochs the validation accuracy is not improving as we arre monitoring the validation accuracy which we want to be maximum¶

In [49]:
es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max', verbose=1, patience=3)

Conclusion¶

It can be seen that the best model turns out to be after carrying out 8 experiments is the one with gradual dropout increase from 0.3 to 0.4 and from 0.4 to 0.5 at the very end of the Convolution layer. This model had 8 Convolutional layers with the stack of the layers increasing in the later part. From the graphs above, this is model with Model 5 as the best model where validation accuracy and validation loss are doing the best job as compared to other models. More number of filters and more number of conv layers stacked at the layer time might be the best option to use.

This best model can change depending on the dataset being used and also if the image classification problem is not binary but multi-class which can have different results altoghter.

Underfitting and overfitting can become problem in the CNN networks so it is good idea to use EarlyStopping in order to save the model overfittting, avoid from training for unnecessary time consuming computation.

Hyper parameters such as Kernel size, number of filters, Pooling technique and size along with dropout play key role in building a robust network.
